---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import AuthorityTimeline from '../../components/diagrams/AuthorityTimeline.astro';
import SilentFailurePlayback from '../../components/diagrams/SilentFailurePlayback.astro';
import DelegationChain from '../../components/diagrams/DelegationChain.astro';
import AuthorityReplay from '../../components/diagrams/AuthorityReplay.astro';
import CurrentVsHistorical from '../../components/diagrams/CurrentVsHistorical.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<Layout title="Authority as a time-bound system — Matt Smithies">
  <Nav />
  <main>
    <article class="px-6">

      {/* ── Header ──────────────────────────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto pt-32 md:pt-40 pb-16">
        <div class="reveal">
          <a href="/#essays" class="text-text-tertiary text-sm hover:text-signal transition-colors mb-8 inline-block">&larr; Back</a>
          <p class="text-signal text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.3em] uppercase mb-4">Authority</p>
          <h1 class="text-gradient text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-display font-bold tracking-tight leading-tight mb-6">
            Authority as a time-bound system
          </h1>
          <p class="text-text-tertiary text-base">
            Authority is not a static property of identity. It is a time-bound claim that must remain replayable if it is to be trusted.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* ── Opening ─────────────────────────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto pb-8">
        <div class="reveal space-y-5 text-text-secondary text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>Most permission models treat authority as static. A user has a role, the role has permissions, the action is allowed. It sounds tidy. It fails in the real world.</p>
          <p>Authority expires. Delegations have windows. A signatory who was authorised three months ago may not be authorised today. A delegate who was valid at 09:00 may be invalid at 09:17. The question is not whether someone has a role. The question is whether they had the authority to perform this action <em class="text-signal not-italic font-medium">at this exact point in time</em>.</p>
          <p>That distinction &mdash; between identity and temporal validity &mdash; is the one most systems fail to make. And it is where the real damage happens, because the system keeps working. No error is thrown. The process continues. The authority behind it has already lapsed. This is the gap between <span class="text-text-primary font-medium">current authority</span> and <span class="text-text-primary font-medium">historical authority</span>, and most architectures do not even acknowledge it exists.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* ── VISUAL 1: Authority timeline ─────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
        <AuthorityTimeline />
      </div>

      {/* ── Carbon as proof, not frame ──────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-16">
        <div class="reveal space-y-5 text-text-secondary text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>Carbon markets make this failure particularly visible. Authorisation of credits involves bounded approvals, delegated signing rights, multi-party verification, and audit obligations that stretch across jurisdictions and time. The actors change. The windows close. The records must survive scrutiny months or years after the fact.</p>
          <p>That makes carbon a useful proving ground. But the underlying problem is not specific to carbon. It appears anywhere approvals, delegated rights, audit obligations, or regulated actions depend on who was entitled to act at a given moment. Financial settlement. Clinical trials. Procurement. Supply chain attestation. Government licensing. The domain changes. The failure mode does not.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* ── Quiet failure ───────────────────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto pb-8">
        <div class="reveal">
          <h2 class="text-text-primary font-display font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl tracking-tight mb-6">Where real systems fail quietly</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal space-y-5 text-text-secondary text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>Not through dramatic compromise. Through ordinary continuation.</p>
          <p>Consider a carbon programme with a delegated regional approver. The programme director delegates signing authority on 11 May with a window that closes on the 18th. On the 17th, the approver submits an approval. Valid. On the 19th, a countersignature is submitted against that same approval. The delegation expired sixteen hours earlier. No replacement grant was issued. The countersignature is recorded. The process moves forward. The authority behind it no longer exists.</p>
          <p>Nobody sees the failure. The interface behaved normally. The event was timestamped. The record looks clean. But the delegation chain was already broken. The gap between recorded action and valid authority is where trust starts to rot &mdash; not through breach, but through continuation under stale legitimacy.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* ── VISUAL 2: Silent failure playback ────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <SilentFailurePlayback />
      </div>

      {/* ── Time as primitive ───────────────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-16">
        <div class="reveal space-y-5 text-text-secondary text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>Treating authority as a time-bound system changes what the model must represent. A grant is not a relationship between two parties. It is a claim with a beginning, often with an end, sometimes with conditions, and sometimes with dependency on another grant above it.</p>
          <p>Once you model that honestly, the old permission model looks naive. It assumes stability where the real world contains turnover, substitution, emergency access, temporary delegation, absence, expiry, and exception.</p>
          <p>Static permission systems are clean because they ignore the thing that makes them hard.</p>
          <p class="text-text-primary font-display font-bold text-2xl pt-4">Time.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* ── VISUAL 3: Delegation chain ───────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <DelegationChain />
      </div>

      {/* ── Accountability ──────────────────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-16">
        <div class="reveal">
          <h2 class="text-text-primary font-display font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl tracking-tight mb-6">Authority is about accountability</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal space-y-5 text-text-secondary text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>When someone acts in a serious system, you need to know four things.</p>

          <div class="border-l-2 border-signal/20 pl-6 my-8">
            <p class="text-text-tertiary text-base font-mono leading-loose">
              Who acted.<br/>
              What they did.<br/>
              When they did it.<br/>
              Why they were entitled to do it then.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p>Most systems can answer the first three after some effort. The fourth is where they become evasive.</p>
          <p>Sometimes because the answer is buried in emails. Sometimes because someone updated a group after the fact and the historical state is gone. Sometimes because the system was never designed to preserve the authority context of the action at all.</p>
          <p>That is not a minor omission. That is the difference between enforceable process and theatre. If the authority state at the time of action cannot be replayed, then what you have is not evidence. It is a retrospective guess dressed as a record.</p>
          <p>That may be enough for an internal dashboard.<br/>It is not enough for regulation.<br/>It is not enough for dispute.<br/>It is not enough for trust between parties who do not already know each other.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* ── VISUAL 4: Authority replay ───────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <AuthorityReplay />
      </div>

      {/* ── Design consequences ─────────────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-16">
        <div class="reveal">
          <h2 class="text-text-primary font-display font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl tracking-tight mb-6">What this demands from the architecture</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal space-y-5 text-text-secondary text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>Without the following properties, the system does not model authority. It reconstructs it after the fact, and reconstruction is not proof.</p>

          <div class="border-l-2 border-signal/20 pl-6 my-8">
            <p class="text-text-tertiary text-base font-mono leading-loose">
              Authority must be versioned over time.<br/>
              Delegation must be explicit, not implied.<br/>
              Expiry must be a native condition, not a manual cleanup.<br/>
              Revocation must be traceable.<br/>
              Historical validity must be queryable at any past moment.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p>And actions that depend on authority must carry a reference to the authority state that made them valid at the time they were taken. Without that binding, history becomes unstable. The same action can look valid today and invalid tomorrow depending on what has changed in the surrounding system.</p>
          <p>That is not a trustworthy record. That is a moving interpretation.</p>
          <p>A serious system must distinguish between two questions.</p>
          <p><span class="text-text-primary font-medium">Current authority</span>: can this actor act now?</p>
          <p><span class="text-text-primary font-medium">Historical authority</span>: was this actor entitled to act then?</p>
          <p>Confuse those two and your audit trail is not a proof. It is a story that changes depending on when you read it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* ── VISUAL 5: Current vs Historical ──────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <CurrentVsHistorical />
      </div>

      {/* ── Closing ─────────────────────────────────────── */}
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-16 pb-24">
        <div class="reveal space-y-5 text-text-secondary text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>This is not a carbon edge case. It is a systems problem that appears anywhere authority, money, risk, machine actions, compliance, or external trust intersect. Wherever a decision carries consequence and a record must survive scrutiny, the question of temporal validity becomes structural. Ignore it and the system works until it is tested. Then it fails in exactly the way described above: silently, historically, and without the evidence needed to understand what went wrong.</p>
          <p>The shortcut is always the same. Treat authority as static. Patch the exceptions later. Hope the process holds.</p>
          <p>It does not.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="reveal border-t border-border pt-10 mt-12">
          <p class="text-text-primary font-display font-bold text-xl md:text-2xl leading-snug max-w-xl">
            If your system cannot answer whether someone was entitled to act at the exact moment they acted, then it does not model authority. It simulates it.
          </p>
        </div>

        {/* ── Live implementation ─────────────────────── */}
        <div class="reveal glass-card p-8 md:p-10 mt-16">
          <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-center gap-6">
            <div class="flex-1">
              <p class="text-signal text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.2em] uppercase mb-2">In production</p>
              <p class="text-text-primary font-display font-bold text-lg md:text-xl tracking-tight mb-2">
                Authority Trail &mdash; Provable authority for carbon markets
              </p>
              <p class="text-text-tertiary text-sm leading-relaxed">
                These principles are not theoretical. Authority Trail implements time-bound authority chains, delegation windows, and replayable verification for carbon credit authorisation.
              </p>
            </div>
            <a href="https://authority.dovu.ai/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="ghost-button magnetic px-6 py-3 rounded-full text-sm whitespace-nowrap flex-shrink-0">
              View the protocol &rarr;
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>

        {/* ── CTA ────────────────────────────────────────── */}
        <div class="reveal glass-card p-8 md:p-10 mt-6 text-center">
          <p class="text-text-secondary text-lg mb-6 font-display">
            Facing these design challenges in your own systems?
          </p>
          <a href="/#contact" class="glow-button magnetic inline-flex items-center gap-3 px-10 py-4 rounded-full text-sm tracking-wide">
            Book a conversation
            <svg class="w-4 h-4" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5">
              <path d="M3 8h10M10 4l4 4-4 4" />
            </svg>
          </a>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8">
          <a href="/#essays" class="text-text-tertiary text-sm hover:text-signal transition-colors">&larr; Back to essays</a>
        </div>
      </div>

    </article>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<script>
  import { initScrollAnimations } from '../../scripts/scroll-animations';
  if (document.readyState === 'loading') {
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initScrollAnimations);
  } else {
    initScrollAnimations();
  }
</script>
